    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Insuring Children</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Michael A Stocker, Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield, regarding Sept 30 article, says New York State did exactly what it should have done about its uninsured children: it went all out to get them covered</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Many Not Eligible in State Program to Insure Children'' (front page, Sept. 30):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Many Not Eligible in State Program to Insure Children'' (front page, Sept. 30):</p>
        <p>New York State did exactly what it should have done about its uninsured children: it went all out to get them covered.</p>
        <p>Both the insurers and New York State have struggled with the handling of Medicaid-eligible Child Health Plus patients, fearing that forcing children to leave one and enroll in the other risked increasing the number of uninsured children.</p>
        <p>The state Health Department worked hard to provide a framework for seamless transitions from Child Health Plus to Medicaid, so the state could comply with federal rules while maintaining coverage for the greatest number of children. The Health Department put the needs of New York's children's first. To do otherwise would have been wrong.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL A. STOCKER, M.D.  New York, Oct. 3, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president and chief executive of Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
